Points, lines, and polygons in R

J Camilo Fagua and Patrick Jantz

August 2023

Objectives

  1. Learn the basic logic and construction of the vector spatial features (points, lines, polygons) in R.

  2. Learn some of the basic operations with vector spatial features in R.

  3. Understand the R logic to process vector spatial features.

  4. Review some of the main R packages to process vector spatial feature in R.

Introduction

This tutorial is focused on providing you the tools required to build, read, and project vector spatial feature in R. There are three main packages used by the R community to bring vector spatial feature data into R: 1) sp, 2) rgdal, and 3) raster. In this tutorial, we also will use the package maptools and tidyverse. Let’s go to start. You need to make sure the following packages are installed and loaded into your RStudio session.

The package sp is the mama-package of all the spatial packages. sp revolutionized the spatial analysis in R when it was built. Team sp created a set of new data classes that integrate the data.frame objects of R with the vector spatial features: points, lines, and polygons. You can see the catalogue of new data classes supported by sp by calling the function getClass().

getClass("Spatial") 
## Class "Spatial" [package "sp"]
## 
## Slots:
##                               
## Name:         bbox proj4string
## Class:      matrix         CRS
## 
## Known Subclasses: 
## Class "SpatialPoints", directly
## Class "SpatialMultiPoints", directly
## Class "SpatialGrid", directly
## Class "SpatialLines", directly
## Class "SpatialPolygons", directly
## Class "SpatialPointsDataFrame", by class "SpatialPoints", distance 2
## Class "SpatialPixels", by class "SpatialPoints", distance 2
## Class "SpatialMultiPointsDataFrame", by class "SpatialMultiPoints", distance 2
## Class "SpatialGridDataFrame", by class "SpatialGrid", distance 2
## Class "SpatialLinesDataFrame", by class "SpatialLines", distance 2
## Class "SpatialPixelsDataFrame", by class "SpatialPoints", distance 3
## Class "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame", by class "SpatialPolygons", distance 2

The subclasses followed by DataFrame in the above catalogue, such as SpatialPointsDataFrame, include additional attributes in the form of a data.frame. For example, if you were working with a SpatialPolygon object, this object would only include the spatial information required to plot the block group polygons. With a SpatialPolygonDataFrame, in a single object, you have both the polygon data and additional data stored in a data.frame (think in the attribute tables of ArcGis or Qgis).

Creating spatial objects from scratch

Spatial points

We are going to start generating a set of 10 points on the unit square [0, 1] and [0, 1]. The function runif() creates random numbers that follow a uniform distribution while the function round() returns rounded values to the specified number of decimal places.

xc = round(runif(10), 2)
yc = round(runif(10), 2)
xy = cbind(xc, yc)
xy
##         xc   yc
##  [1,] 0.62 0.48
##  [2,] 0.41 0.47
##  [3,] 0.74 0.97
##  [4,] 0.44 0.24
##  [5,] 0.37 0.44
##  [6,] 0.27 0.09
##  [7,] 0.60 0.41
##  [8,] 0.95 0.64
##  [9,] 0.91 0.77
## [10,] 0.25 0.67
class(xy)
## [1] "matrix" "array"

The matrix xy can be converted into a SpatialPoints object by the function SpatialPoints. You can observe the change of the object type by using the function class().

xy.sp = SpatialPoints(xy)
class(xy.sp)
## [1] "SpatialPoints"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"
xy.sp
## class       : SpatialPoints 
## features    : 10 
## extent      : 0.25, 0.95, 0.09, 0.97  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## crs         : NA

Although the Coordinate Reference System (CRS) argument is NA (Not-Available), we can plot and retrieve the coordinates of xy.sp because this is a spatial object. Observe that xy.cc is a matrix.

plot(xy.sp, pch = 2)

xy.cc = coordinates(xy.sp)
class(xy.cc)
## [1] "matrix" "array"

You can obtain the coordinates and spatial bounding of xy.sp with the functions coordinates() and bbox(), respectively. This type of information can be useful when you are working with polygons created by other people.

We can also create points with attributes (SpatialPointsDataFrame) by building them from a SpatialPoints object (such as xy.sp) and a data.frame containing the attributes.

Spatial lines

Spatial lines are retrieved from external sources frequently; however, the following example show how to build an object of class SpatialLines from scratch. We firstly create the points that lines are going to follow. We secondly create the lines using these points and the function Line(). We thirdly put these lines in a list separately; these lines are not spatial object at this point. We finally merge both lines and give spatial properties with the function SpatialLines(). Note that the lines objects must be given character ID values, and that these values must be unique for Lines objects combined in a SpatialLines objects.

# To create the points that the lines follow. 
l1 = cbind(c(1,2,3),c(3,2,2))
l1a = cbind(l1[,1]+.05,l1[,2]+.05)
l2 = cbind(c(1,2,3),c(1,1.5,1))

# To create the lines.
Sl1 = Line(l1)
Sl1a = Line(l1a)
Sl2 = Line(l2)

# To put these lines in a list separately.
S1 = Lines(list(Sl1, Sl1a), ID="a")
S2 = Lines(list(Sl2), ID="b")
#
Sl = SpatialLines(list(S1,S2))
summary(Sl)
## Object of class SpatialLines
## Coordinates:
##   min  max
## x   1 3.05
## y   1 3.05
## Is projected: NA 
## proj4string : [NA]
plot(Sl)

We can create a SpatialLines object with attributes by attaching an attribute table (data.frame). In the next codes, the function sapply() applies the function slot() to each line object to generate an ID.

df_2 = data.frame(z = c(1,2), row.names=sapply(slot(Sl, "lines"), function(x) slot(x, "ID")))
Sldf = SpatialLinesDataFrame(Sl, data = df_2)
summary(Sldf)

Spatial Polygons

Now we will build polygons from scratch. The function cbind() allows the construction of the points that form the polygons while the function Polygon() creates no-spatial polygons. The argument hole = TRUE of Sr4 is for setting a polygon as hole.

#To create no-spatial polygons 
Sr1 = Polygon(cbind(c(2,4,4,1,2),c(2,3,5,4,2)))
Sr2 = Polygon(cbind(c(5,4,2,5),c(2,3,2,2)))
Sr3 = Polygon(cbind(c(4,4,5,10,4),c(5,3,2,5,5)))
Sr4 = Polygon(cbind(c(5,6,6,5,5),c(4,4,3,3,4)), hole = TRUE)
Sr1@coords #To see coordinates
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    2    2
## [2,]    4    3
## [3,]    4    5
## [4,]    1    4
## [5,]    2    2
#To put the polygons in a list and add IDs ("s1","s2","s3").
Srs1 = Polygons(list(Sr1), "s1")
Srs2 = Polygons(list(Sr2), "s2")
Srs3 = Polygons(list(Sr3, Sr4), "s3/s4")

Note that the Polygons objects must be given character ID values, and that these values must be unique for Polygons objects combined in a SpatialPolygons object. Now we are going to create the spatial polygon.

#To create the final spatial polygons and plot it.
SpP = SpatialPolygons(list(Srs1,Srs2,Srs3), 1:3)
plot(SpP, col = 1:3)

As we did for spatial point and lines, we can attach attributes to the spatial polygons. Polygons with attributes (objects of class SpatialPolygonsDataFrame) are built from the SpatialPolygons object (topology) and the attributes (data.frame). The row.names of the attributes data frame are matched with the ID slots of the SpatialPolygons object, and the rows of the data frame will be re-ordered if necessary.

attr = data.frame(a=1:3, row.names=c("s3/s4", "s2", "s1"))
attr
##       a
## s3/s4 1
## s2    2
## s1    3
SrDf = SpatialPolygonsDataFrame(SpP, attr)
SrDf
## class       : SpatialPolygonsDataFrame 
## features    : 3 
## extent      : 1, 10, 2, 5  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## crs         : NA 
## variables   : 1
## names       : a 
## min values  : 1 
## max values  : 3
as(SrDf, "data.frame")
##       a
## s1    3
## s2    2
## s3/s4 1
spplot(SrDf)# the function spplot() is a method for plotting spatial data with attributes.

NOTE: By creating the previous spatial features from scratch, you understand the basic logic and structure that R and the other software use to create spatial data. This information could be important when you start to analyze your own data.

Loading and operating existing shapefiles into R

The data required to visualize a single shapefile in Arc or QGIS is split into many files (e.g., cpg, .dbf, .prj, etc.), the most known of which is the sacred .SHP file (do you know the function of the other files?). To get all this info into an organized spatial object in R is easy, and in fact, as is often the case in R, there are multiple packages and functions that will do this for you. Here are a few of the most used options to read .SHP of the packages rgdal, maptools, raster, and sf:

library(rgdal)
DEPARTMENTS_1 = readOGR(dsn = ".", layer = "MGN_DPTO_POLITICO") #no .shp required
## Warning: OGR support is provided by the sf and terra packages among others

## Warning: OGR support is provided by the sf and terra packages among others
## Warning: OGR support is provided by the sf and terra packages among others

However, the use the rgdal option is the most appropriate for large or complex shapefiles with multiple layers because of its efficiency to operate. You also can see 1) the bounding box at coordinates, 2) the geographic projection at proj4string, and 3) the data attributes with some general statistics (depending on the type of attribute: numeric, character, other). The attribute selection by subsetting is based on logical operators (e.g. ==, |, &, >=, $). You can find many guides to use this type of operators; one of these guides is in towards data science;. You can also subset by the interaction of attributes using logical operators. For instance, a group 1 with the departments larger than the average size (DPTO_NAREA; values in km2) that were created before 1950. Or a group 2 with the departments in the quartile 1 (the smallest) created after 1950.

#Group 1
Size = mean(DEPARTMENTS_1$DPTO_NAREA)#To obtain the mean

Crop(clip)

You also can crop input features that overlay a clip feature. You can use crops to cut out a piece of one feature class using one or more of the features in another feature class as a cookie cutter with the function crop(). We are going to load the .SHP of the Colombian amazon region to crop the departments that are in the region.

Projections and centroids

The function gCentroid() calculates the centroid of the given geometry. Let’s go to calculate them for CAUCA_MUNI

CAUCA_MUNI@proj4string
## Coordinate Reference System:
## Deprecated Proj.4 representation: +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs 
## WKT2 2019 representation:
## GEOGCRS["WGS 84",
##     DATUM["World Geodetic System 1984",
##         ELLIPSOID["WGS 84",6378137,298.257223563,
##             LENGTHUNIT["metre",1]]],
##     PRIMEM["Greenwich",0,
##         ANGLEUNIT["degree",0.0174532925199433]],
##     CS[ellipsoidal,2],
##         AXIS["latitude",north,
##             ORDER[1],
##             ANGLEUNIT["degree",0.0174532925199433]],
##         AXIS["longitude",east,
##             ORDER[2],
##             ANGLEUNIT["degree",0.0174532925199433]],
##     ID["EPSG",4326]]
CENT = gCentroid(CAUCA_MUNI, byid=TRUE)
plot(CENT)

plot(CAUCA_MUNI)
plot(CENT, add=T, col = "red")

Now, we can estimate the matrix of distances among the centroids. However, R shows a warming: Spatial object 1 is not projected; GEOS expects planar coordinates. You as spatial analyst knows that the right estimation of distances or areas needs a planar projection, and our polygons are in geographic projection.

dist_matrix <- gDistance(spgeom1 = CENT, spgeom2 = NULL, byid=T)
## Warning in RGEOSDistanceFunc(spgeom1, spgeom2, byid, "rgeos_distance"): Spatial
## object 1 is not projected; GEOS expects planar coordinates
dist_matrix[1:4, 1:4]
##           299       300      301       302
## 299 0.0000000 0.1815861 1.530989 0.1026708
## 300 0.1815861 0.0000000 1.688305 0.1822681
## 301 1.5309886 1.6883047 0.000000 1.6083476
## 302 0.1026708 0.1822681 1.608348 0.0000000

Therefore, we need to change the geographic projection of CAUCA_MUNI to a planar projection. We are going to use UTM at the 18-north zone, the appropriate UTM for the Cauca, using the function spTransform. See the CRS or coordinate reference system arguments, the nomenclature of this argument is explained at here. What is the units of the distances ?

Figure 1. UTM zones.
CAUCA_MUNI_UTM18 = spTransform(CAUCA_MUNI, CRSobj="+proj=utm +zone=18 +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs")
proj4string(CAUCA_MUNI_UTM18)
## [1] "+proj=utm +zone=18 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs"
CENT_UTM18 = gCentroid(CAUCA_MUNI_UTM18, byid=T)
plot(CENT_UTM18)

#
plot(CAUCA_MUNI_UTM18)
plot(CENT_UTM18, add=T, col = "purple")

dist_matrix_UTM18 <- gDistance(spgeom1 = CENT_UTM18, spgeom2 = NULL, byid=T)
dist_matrix_UTM18[1:4, 1:4]

Buffers

Buffer is a technique commonly used to determine areas that are proximal to certain objects. Traditionally, buffers are circular.

house_buffers_1 <- gBuffer(CENT_UTM18, width = 5000, byid = TRUE)
## Warning: GEOS support is provided by the sf and terra packages among others
plot(house_buffers_1)

But R is so flexible, you can obtain square and lineal buffers also. However the lineal is incompatible with SpatialPoints geometries.

house_buffers_2 <- gBuffer(CENT_UTM18, width = 5000, byid = TRUE, capStyle = "SQUARE")
## Warning: GEOS support is provided by the sf and terra packages among others
plot(house_buffers_2)

house_buffers_3 <- gBuffer(CAUCA_MUNI_UTM18, width = 5000, byid = TRUE, capStyle = "FLAT")
## Warning: GEOS support is provided by the sf and terra packages among others
plot(house_buffers_3)
